This is a great series. Dick Van Dyke is such a wonderful actor. You will love this series. You won't be disappointed.

While I definitely enjoyed the series as a whole, and some of the episodes of season 8, it became clear that season 8 was the Van Dyke Family Hour season as fewer and fewer episodes took advantage of what Jesse and Amanda brought to the ensemble to showcase Barry Van Dyke's kids... who, to be honest, mostly fall flat.

However, as this is the final season, it is definitely worth owning to round out the series (especially, now that it's available separately without having to purchase the complete collection.)

A have-to for those who have waited all these years for the final seasons to be released.  The last season showcases each member of the cast and gives viewers what appears to be an inside look at the loving relationship between father and son, on screen as well as off.  You will relive some of the most exciting and touching episodes if you saw the original series.  If not, you will be sorry this is the last season.

Diagnosis Murder season eight, in which the series goes out not with style and grace but a whimper, bogged down by nepotism.  At this point, series regulars Charlie Schlatter (Dr. Jesse Travis) and Victoria Rowell (Dr. Amanda Bentley) are seriously downgraded to mere guest stars rarely used.  In their place, they favored Barry Van Dykes children instead, shoehorning them in whenever they could.  Otherwise, the series limped along the same as usual, repeating gags and bits long overused.  Dick Van Dyke is still doing magic, still singing, still dancingall at the oddest times.  Familiarity does breed contempt.
